The evidence is very suggestive, but I am bothered by the lack of attention to socioeconomic factors that we know to be co-variant with race and ethnicity and, one might surmise, also with Vitamin D levels and COVID risk. The chart in lower left at 36.49 is a case in point. Here it is shown that for each race separately, positive rates of COVID tests are correlated with decreasing D levels in the blood. And yet, the variation across the entire spectrum of D level for whites is smaller than the variation for the other races, and even at the lowest D level, whites are less likely to test positive than Blacks or Hispanics at the higher D levels. This finding is consistent with the notion that general levels of nutrition and health, which are lower among Blacks than among whites, as well as the fact that lower-income people tend to live in closer quarters with others and work in jobs (waiting tables, driving taxis, etc.) where they come into contact with many more people, are at least as important as D levels alone in explaining these patterns. Indeed, one could speculate that the higher rates of test positivity for whites with Vitamin D deficiency compared to whites with good D levels, could be entirely explained by poor nutrition and general health (which make them more susceptible to infection) and low income (resulting in more frequent contact with other people who might be infected) for that cohort, rather than by D levels alone. I'm prepared to be convinced otherwise, but feel this is a major gap in this video.

Fat stores vitamin D,  but  the vitamin D that enters adipose fat can eventually leave that fat.  So I would argue that adipose fat doesn't reduce the amount of vitamin D in your blood, but rather it is more correct to say that it introduces a time lag into the system.  A metaphor would be that a dam on river. A dam stores water, but a dam doesn't reduce overall the amount of water in the river below it.  Rather, a dam introduces a time a lag into the when the water gets to the river.   Of course, the water behind the dam is actually evaporating, so that complicates the metaphor.

Further thoughts. It's noted that Finland fortifies their dairy products with vitamin D. Possibly why the have had such success in dealing with C-19. Vitamin D has been recognised to regulate the adaptive immune system ( here at 22:22) . This is why it has been so successful in C-19 symptom severity reduction. Consider that the adaptive immune response (cytokine storms, macrophage and T Cell activity against self) are hallmarks of autoimmune diseases (Type 1 diabetes, Multiple Sclerosis, etc) as well as C-19. 

After mandating vitamin D be added to dairy products in 2003 the Finnish youth population saw their collective serum vitamin D content rise from ~65 nmol/L to ~80 nmol/L (Makinen et al (2014) which shortly thereafter saw the incidence of type 1 diabetes plateau (Harjutsalo et al 2013). This escalation of serum vitamin D was enough to be effective yet it was not optimal. I propose that if the serum content was elevated to an ideal 110  nmol/l the incidence would have plummeted to zero.

Notably the type 1 diabetes problem in Finland  became more pronounced after the 1950s, Harjutsalo et al 2013 noted, when the amount of vitamin D recommended for supplementation in infants was reduced to one-tenth and the incidence of T1D increased fivefold.  BTW Canada does indeed fortify their milk with vitamin D but it's in no where near high enough concentrations to regulate the adaptive immune response, which is why they have such high prevalences of T1D and MS etc.

ConsumerLab advises that total serum 25-hydroxyvitamin D level should not exceed 39 ng/mL. They state that the IOM (Institute of Medicine) cautions against serum levels >= 50 ng/mL, citing adverse effects shown in various studies including increases in some cancers, CVD, fractures and falls, and even overall mortality (starting as low as 30 ng/mL). 

I notice a lot of the cited studies are older, and probably many should be disregarded for one reason or another. But the number of studies is worrisome, as well as some newer ones such as an NHANES study in 2019, and a Canadian study also in 2019 and followup in 2020.

Also, the NIH fact sheet on Vit D: https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/VitaminD-HealthProfessional/ has a table that states >50 ng/mL serum levels are "linked to potential adverse effects, particularly at > 60 ng/mL".

If you read Michael Hollick's recent paper with a co-author you will see that one of the most fascinating things about vitamin D is that it's simultaneously improves pathogen resistance by increasing/up regulating anti pathogen proteins that are part of immune defense and at the same time clamping down on several families of pro-inflammatory cytokines implicated in sepsis and so-called cytokine storm. In other words it is both able to improve immune competence while dampening the destructive effects of inflammation on our own tissues. We have seen widespread uncritical acceptance of the meme from the Institute of Medicine that anything over 30 is an adequate level. A boatload of research suggests that a desirable target level is actually more like 45 to 65. An interesting question in that regard is at what level does the body start storing excess vitamin D in body fat. That appears to happen over 50 suggesting that that is the target we should be aiming for. In other words evolution created that set point for transition to storage because that was the level we needed to achieve in order to get through the more sunlight deprived winter months. This is a very valuable talk.

I am a retired general surgeon. Back in about 2005 an article in the orthopedic literature showed that patients with low vitamin D levels had a high risk of postoperative wound infection. Thereafter I obtained vitamin D levels on every one of my patients who presented for elective surgery. If their vitamin D levels were not optimal I placed them on 5000 units of vitamin D3 per day along with high doses of diet vitamin C and broad-spectrum multivitamins, In preparation for their elective surgery. I also obtained vitamin D levels on patients that presented in the emergency room with necrotizing fasciitis or necrotizing cellulitis. Not surprisingly, every one of these severely infected patients had very low levels of vitamin D, less than about 15. 
In 2013, I took over the care of a postoperative patient for another surgeon who was going on a short vacation. This patient had been on the ventilator for a few weeks, a “chronic lunger,“ very frail, unable to overcome the work of breathing sufficiently to get off the ventilator. The day after I took over I had to take her back to surgery because her ileostomy had to necrosed; this required opening the abdomen again to mobilize the ileum and create a new ileostomy: obviously not good for her lungs. Soon her vitamin D level came back: “<3,” that is, immeasurable. I asked Pharmacy to put 50,000 units of vitamin D in her tube feedings daily, which the primary surgeon continued upon his return a few days later. Within 48 hours she had gained strength enough to be extubated and within a few weeks she was discharged from the hospital. Only an anecdote, but I was impressed. I keep my vitamin D levels at about 70, for which I take 6500 international units vit D3 per day, as part of a broad-spectrum regimen to support the immune system.

An excellent presentation. It is likely that the mechanism of efficacy pertaining to vitamin D3 is its membrane anti-oxidative potential. The supportive epidemiological data has been quite impressive. I think that the cytokine similarity between Covid19 and vitamin D deficiency may be slightly spurious. While Covid19  may induce a cytokine milieu that includes those that may occur as a consequence of Th1 and Th17 (this is not to say that either Th1 or Th17 are particularly activated in Covid19), vitamin D3 is known to interfere with Th1 and Th17 expression. Thus a deficiency in vitamin D3 might be said to permit excesses in IL-6 etc. that might otherwise characterise a Th17 response. As for the severity in population group with Covid19 and its overlap with the vitamin D deficient, this analysis needs verification. One of the conclusions that I had reached in a rather modest narrative review, published in the online only European Medical Journal entitled 'Primer on the pathogenesis of severe Covid19' - in 2 parts, was that the populations in which severe Covid19 manifested all tended to have pre-existing high levels of Protein Kinase R (a viral response element) which also happens to form part of the integrated stress response (as in for example obesity, diabetes, CVD, the elderly).
